## Summary

Adds a config-level `dataHandling` policy surface for privacy/data-handling conformance. This is the next policy-stack slice after #85572, #85744, and #86768. Because those upstream stack PRs are still open, GitHub currently shows their commits in this draft PR too; the data-handling commit in this branch is `6fe6f00305f`.

The posture model stays the same: observe configured settings, report non-conformance, and avoid runtime enforcement or content inspection.

New policy syntax:

```jsonc
{
  "dataHandling": {
    "sensitiveLogging": {
      "requireRedaction": true
    },
    "telemetry": {
      "denyContentCapture": true
    },
    "retention": {
      "requireSessionMaintenance": true
    },
    "memory": {
      "denySessionTranscriptIndexing": true
    }
  },
  "scopes": {
    "restricted-agents": {
      "agentIds": ["release-agent", "support-agent"],
      "dataHandling": {
        "memory": {
          "denySessionTranscriptIndexing": true
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

What is checked:

| Policy field | Observed config posture | Finding when |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `dataHandling.sensitiveLogging.requireRedaction` | `logging.redactSensitive` | redaction is explicitly `"off"` |
| `dataHandling.telemetry.denyContentCapture` | `diagnostics.otel.captureContent` plus active OTEL trace/log export posture | telemetry content capture is enabled |
| `dataHandling.retention.requireSessionMaintenance` | `session.maintenance.mode` | effective mode is not `"enforce"` |
| `dataHandling.memory.denySessionTranscriptIndexing` | `memory.qmd.sessions.enabled` and `agents.*.memorySearch` session sources | session transcript memory indexing is enabled |

Scope support is intentionally narrow: only `dataHandling.memory.denySessionTranscriptIndexing` is agent-scoped through `agentIds`. Global logging, telemetry, and retention rules remain top-level because their evidence is not agent-attributable.

Boundary: this PR does not inspect raw logs, telemetry exports, transcript contents, memory files, secrets, or personal data. It checks whether config settings conform to policy.

